content:
So back in July I had tall fescue turf laid in my back yard*. It's mostly doing great. But there's a few patches that are struggling, one or two look to be outright dead.

I'm going to oversow with seed, but I'm still trying to get to the bottom of why it's doing badly. A couple of weeks ago I fertilised the whole lawn, but that hasn't really helped.

Based on the fact that there's a couple of very small spots, like a few inches across, of dead grass, I'm starting to suspect grubs. So today I started spot-applying a pesticide / fertiliser / wetter.

But apart from that I'm not sure what to do. The only other theory I have, based on the fact that some of the poor sections coincide with where I remember the original surface being higher, is that the topsoil brought in wasn't well combined with what was already there. And the grass can't get roots in to the shitty soil under eat? Dunno. But if that's the case then I'm not sure I can do much about it until I aerate the soil and put down some top dressing. And with this grass that feels like more of an autumn job?

* Yes, grass lawns aren't the best. I need space for a child to play in, and the majority of our yard is gardens.

content:
@xris since I've seen you boosting some stuff about instances defederating tech.lgbt: just so you know, the context is that one of their mods played a role in instigating a major racist dogpile against a well-known Black user earlier this year. The tech.lgbt administration believes the mod's role was minimal and that they've addressed the issue appropriately (https://info.tech.lgbt/2023/10/13/thebadspace-situation.html); other admins (some from notably stricter servers) disagree.

I seem to recall this isn't the first time tech.lgbt has shit the bed (I think a mod/admin got dogpiled, handled it badly, and threatened to shut the server down?) but I can't remember the details. (They are silenced on flipping.rocks.)

All this is to say, this is pretty standard as far as reasons for defederation go, and while you may think the admins are wrong to choose to defederate, this is not a random interpersonal beef or impulse decision as some recent major defederations have been.

content:
All these sites like Youtube/Facebook/Twitter/Reddit started their businesses on the backs of the same lie. They intentionally put forth an unsustainable business model, operating at a financial loss, in the hope that they could then turn around and sell the userbase they accrued to advertisers. They steal from and underpay content creators, moderators, and volunteer staff who began working expecting to contribute to a community. They changed the experience for the users to shove ads in faces, then they started charging the advertisers more and more to get their ads in front of users. They started their sites with lies and theft, continued lying to carry it forward, and are hoping after the fact to convince us we should pay for it.

Is there a name for that kind of scheme? It's almost like a ponzi, except in this case the 'money' is the userbase and creators, and the suckers are the advertisers.

In this case though we can at least partially hurt the advertisers, which is good!

You should continue to use uBlock Origin and other successful ad blockers as long as you can. Use video and audio downloaders to pirate as much of the content as you can/want. On the services that allow it, report all the ads for offensive content, spam, incitement to violence, etc. IDK about you but I feel violent when an ad for some piece of shit I didn't want interrupts the content I want, so it's apt.

While you do all that, revel in the fact that they're burning money, time, programmer skill, energy/computer time, and user/advertiser good will at a feverish pace to try to plug all the holes in this gazebo they tried to make into a ship.

Burn them as hard as you can, then move on to a more equitable content sharing site if they ever succeed.

"We're spinning up a new team, and we want you to come do the same thing for us again."

That'd been my last MFC project, and I had moved on, and I tried to explain that to them.

"Oh! No, not MFC, this project is Python. No. We want you to come show this team how to do all that shit we forbade you to do when you were here the first time but did anyway."

:)

content:
There are several ways to handle apparent conflicts of interest.

For example:

* You can _disclose_ the conflict and acknowledge it. I maintained my criticism of the #FSEP proposal here in part because it didn't disclose the relationship between the author of the proposal and TBS.

* You can have another group or entity that has a lower stake in the question make the decision or be able to overrule the decision. This is how, e.g., nonprofits work

5/
